snippet.textDisplay:
I believe everything he said. He seems to know his aviation stuff. The way he was explaining it, he has a keen knowledge about aviation and how a plane/helicopter flies.

To those that don't know, you can't fly a helicopter above your clouds. You lose visibility and contact. You have to fly between the clouds and the grounds to be able to maintain visibility and contact.

If you in the clouds....in this case, the fog, you lose all awareness of your grounds/terrain, and flying blind. You suppose to maintain a distance between the clouds' ceiling and your grounds.

If you under the cloud ceiling, and the terrains looks high (flying close to the grounds) you are flying too low, and putting pressure on the rotors which cause the Helicopter to slow down considerably the lower you keep getting to the grounds.

Basically, you're about to crash the copter because the lower you get, the slower the copter and ultimately the rotors will stop and the engine will idle or shuts off and BOOM! You crash.

In Kobe' situation, the Pilot was trying to swerve out of the heavy fog. You do that by circling away from your projected path and climb upward, above the clouds to re-establish visibility and your terrain.

Well, when he was trying to swerve out of the fog, he was already too low and the rotors stopped at that point and slammed smacked into the hillside.

Kobe and the guests that was with him, would have been better off jumping from the copter at that point. It wouldnt have been an ideal situation but with death on the line, what would you do?

I'm just distraught right now. It's like I feel close to Kobe and Gigi, and lost family members. It's so sad it hurts. It hurts like hell.

R.I.P. to the all the victims.
